description.plain:
‘The Barrel’ is a mysterious song that has little discernible meaning, and Harding likes it this way. In NPR’s ‘All Songs Considered’ article, she said,“I realized that the video was a well-intended opinion of mine to just keep it loose,” she says in our conversation. “I feel we’re expected to be able to explain ourselves after we’ve worked the space and have purpose, you know, in a little bag that you carry around everywhere. But I don’t necessarily have that in me the way you might think.”

Regardless of Harding’s refusal to define the song’s meaning, many people have theorised the topic is about childbirth or possibly miscarriage, given the multiple references to symbols of fertilitity and babies like doves, eggs, a date being set, death, and direct mentions of a child.

annotations: Show the ferret to the egg

Ferrets eat eggs.

This could represent intentionally ending something before it’s even had the chance to begin

I know you have the dove
 I’m not gettin’ wet

In conversation with Bob Boilen of NPR, Harding states:

Basically, […] when I’m saying, “I know you have the dove”, [it’s] a trick, and I’m not going to get wet for a trick.  I’m not going to dive in for something that ultimately [I don’t believe.] […] And the thing is, it’s not a lifestyle, it’s just a thought.  Some days I live it, other days I belong to everybody, as far as I’m concerned.  I’m very open.  And then other days, you know, I write songs like that.

When you have a child, so begins the braiding
 And in that braid you stay

In conversation with Bob Boilen of NPR, Harding states:

[It’s about] the finality of commitment. […] Being a free spirit, but not being free in that.  Wanting those things, or wanting to want those things, but unfortunately being filled with a lot of doubt and distrust.

Interestingly, ‘braids’ and ‘braiding’ are also mentioned in ‘Treasure’, as “the braided cover of my love”.

description.plain:
Opening 2017’s Party, Harding describes missing a lover intensely. She reminisces on important moments of their relationship in detail and frames him as her “perfect man” – an issue she goes on to grapple with in the following track, ‘Imagining My Man’.

Harding told BrooklynVega about the song’s creation,

“The song was written in an AirBnB in Bristol the night before going into the studio.”

description.plain:
“Stop Your Tears” is the album opener for Harding’s self-titled debut album. It sets the moody, dark tone of the record, filled with religious imagery and references to death in relation to romance.

To TheMusicAU in 2019, Harding revealed the song was about losing her mind.

body.plain:
“Stop Your Tears” is the album opener for Harding’s self-titled debut album. It sets the moody, dark tone of the record, filled with religious imagery and references to death in relation to romance.

To TheMusicAU in 2019, Harding revealed the song was about losing her mind.

annotations: Hold her head above the water

In reference to the previous line being the River Styx, it could signify that she is attempting to prevent her child from passing from the land of the living into the underworld. However, it should also be noted that the River Styx held magical properties in which anyone immersed would be made invulnerable. Much like Achilles when he was dipped into the River Styx wherein all but his ankle was immersed rendering him vulnerable there, the author believes she sparing her child and “holding her head above water”.  Despite the author’s attempts and intentions she has rendered her child ultimately vulnerable.
I am at the river with baby
She could possibly be referencing the river Styx that forms a border between the underworld and the world of the living, where sinners were punished.

The yellow rose is a stranger
 The devil’s invitation in bloom

The yellow rose signifies appreciation, friendship, optimism and in Eastern cultures, wisdom. If the yellow rose is a stranger than the author is saying that her existence lacks these qualities and therefore ‘the devil’s invitation’ (e.g. ingratitude, isolation, pessimism, and ignorance) seems a bit more appealing or ‘in bloom'

I will never marry my love
 I will die waiting for the bells
The narrator states the futility in longing for her love. And that the two of them will never be together. Never in a lifetime, and hence, she will die waiting for the ring of the church bells.

The Virgin Mary hangs on the door
 
 I will arrive at death’s border
 Take back the cover God has torn from me

Harding told The Guardian in 2014 that religious imagery appeared throughout the Aldous Harding album as a representation of her mental state:

(The religious imagery is) strictly to do with the mild psychosis that was happening […] a manifestation of what was happening inside my head during a nervous breakdown.

The Virgin Mary, mother of Jesus Christ is an important figure in Christianity, particularly to Catholics, who recognise her as a saintly figure. Catholics will often own pendants with the image of Blessed Virgin Mary, to receive “good graces” and act as a declaration of faith.
Baudelaire in the afternoon
Charles Baudelaire was a French poet, who, along with publishing his own works, translated Edgar Allan Poe’s work from English to French.
Death, come pull me underwater

“Deep down into our lungs at every breathing,
death flows, an unseen river, moaning dirges.”
- Baudelaire, Les Fleurs du Mal, prologue/To the Reader
I was born the day the year was new
Literally that she was born the 1st of January, but it connects her birth, a new life with the new year. A chance for starting afresh.

annotations:
Oh, the dirty of it
 Ripped the label
 You were chosen man
 Holy

The narrator’s foil, referred to as “You” or “him,” could possess a kind of gravitas or ease in the public eye that the narrator can’t help but notice.

“He” is magnetic enough that it nearly seems subversive, as if he was predestined for public life.

Party people, they all want to start at me
 All I want is an office in the country

Here, the narrator seems frustrated by the attention of others, especially those who only seem superficially interested.

“An office in the country” is perhaps another reference to Henry Moore, who studied sheep from the window of his office in pastoral Hertfordshire.

The narrator seems to covet a quiet place to work, as opposed to working under the attention of an audience.

Put in the context of Moore’s country office, we might also interpret this lyric to mean that the narrator wants to study and experience the world from a safe distance, without having to participate.

Wanted to see me, what you gonna do?
 Now that you see me
 Tick tock

The narrator seems to express anxiety about being known or “seen.” It can argued that this theme is present in other songs on Warm Chris, like the later track “Staring at the Henry Moore.”

The lyrics suggest that once the narrator is “seen,” it’s only a matter of time before the “party people” mentioned earlier withdraw.

annotations: Will you die on the vine, choosing it over?

This might be referencing a passage in The Bell Jar by Sylvia Plath: “I saw my life branching out before me like the green fig tree in the story. From the tip of every branch, like a fat purple fig, a wonderful future beckoned and winked… . I saw myself sitting in the crotch of this fig tree, starving to death, just because I couldn’t make up my mind which of the figs I would choose. I wanted each and every one of them, but choosing one meant losing all the rest, and, as I sat there, unable to decide, the figs began to wrinkle and go black, and, one by one, they plopped to the ground at my feet.”
The braided cover of love

Olivia Horn from Pitchfork notes the importance of “braiding” throughout the Designer record:

The concept of braiding is significant: It taps into a totalizing fear of making life choices that might ensnare you, as plaits tamp down flyaways.

annotations: Fingers of love

A phrase possibly taken from another internationally renowned New Zealand musical act

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iLFpWo3i6VY

When you watch me play, does it feel bad, darlin’
 When they choose me?

Harding dated New Zealand musician, Marlon Williams, for several years prior to the release of “Horizon.” However, they both grew up in Lyttleton, Christchurch, New Zealand and likely met through the local music scene. It is also apparent that Harding asked Williams to co-produce her debut album when plans began in 2012.

The pair broke up in December of 2016. William’s website bio describes their career paths as crucial to their split:

(This was) the end of a relationship that brought together two of Down Under’s most acclaimed talents of recent years, who’d managed to navigate the challenges of having equally ascendant—though separate—careers, until they couldn’t.

With this lyric, Harding implies she has experienced greater success, despite William’s two New Zealand Music Awards and ARIA award nomination.
For your wounds, babe
This could be the wounds she has left, or will leave. It could also simply be a way to convey tenderness toward someone she loves.

And every now and then, I think about
 When you’ll die, babe
 There’s a fall in my head
 It floods what you said into the room, babe
 I don’t belong in the desert
 Yes, I can see it, take me home, babe
 Say again, this place
 Say again, this place
 Here is your princess
 And here is the horizon
 Here is your princess
 And here is the horizon

The writer says she thinks about when her lover will die. While this sounds morbid, there is the possibility that she does it for her own good-she loves this person, but she simply must go, no matter how much she may miss them.
Say again, this place

I think the line is, “Sigh again, this place”

PROPOSED SUGGESTION: While she is singing the line in a stylized way, if you listen to multiple live versions of the song, she’s clearly singing the word “say”.
And now the sugar’s run out
Time to move on.

Here is your princess
 And here is the horizon
A striking line that contrasts the present and the future. The writer wants to not be held back by anything and to go on towards the horizon (destiny) moment.
